    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-04-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-04-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="876"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d876">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">817.51/4–246: Airgram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Warren</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Managua</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-04-02">April 2,
                            1946</date>.<lb/>[Received April 5—9:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_A1">A</gloss>–115. Reference is made to the Department’s
                    Airgram <gloss target="#t_A1">A</gloss>–58 of March 5, 1946, concerning
                    Nicaragua’s arrears in the amount of $86,063.38 in payment of its Export-Import
                    Bank loan. I had a good opportunity to discuss the matter with President Somoza
                    at El Genizaro.<note n="33" xml:id="d876fn33">The President’s country
                        home.</note>
                </p>
                <p>I allowed the President to read Airgram No. <gloss target="#t_A1">A</gloss>–58.
                    He said: <list>
                        <label>(1)</label>
                        <item>That he and Ambassador Sevilla Sacasa are not trying to link the
                            Export-Import Bank loan to the <gloss target="#t_Pan1"
                            >Pan</gloss>-American Highway accounts.</item>
                        <label>(2)</label>
                        <item>That he only wants Washington to wait a bit until settlement of the
                            Highway accounts is accomplished in the hope that Nicaragua will then be
                            in a better position to meet the obligation.</item>
                        <label>(3)</label>
                        <item>That because the audit of the <gloss target="#t_Pan1"
                            >Pan</gloss>-American Highway accounts had proceeded slowly, he had had
                            to use the money set aside for payment of the Export-Import Bank loan to
                            finance the highway expenditures.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Warren</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
